Executive summary

This analysis explores the relationship between a set of variables in mtcars dataset and addresses the following questions:

  • Is an automatic or manual transmission better for MPG?
  • Quantify the MPG difference between automatic and manual transmissions.

The analysis will shows that even though there is difference between the cars with manual and automatic transmission with respect to MPG, the manual transmission is no better than automatic transmission judging by information collected in the dataset.

The dataset

The data mtcars is available in R datasets packages. The data was extracted from the 1974 Motor Trend US magazine, and comprises fuel consumption and 10 aspects of automobile design and performance for 32 automobiles (197374 models). Format: A data frame with 32 observations on 11 variables.

Feature Description
mpg Miles/(US) gallon
cyl Number of cylinders
disp Displacement (cu.in.)
hp Gross horsepower
drat Rear axle ratio
wt Weight (1000 lbs)
qsec 1/4 mile time
vs V/S
am Transmission (0 = automatic, 1 = manual)
gear Number of forward gears
carb Number of carburetors

The source code for data transformations is available in Appendix A.

Pairs plot of the dataset is available in Appendix B.

The boxplot shows that MPG is higher for the manual transmission. Lets check this with a t-test.

t.test(mpg ~ am, data = dataset)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mpg by am
## t = -3.7671, df = 18.332, p-value = 0.001374
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -11.280194  -3.209684
## sample estimates:
##   mean in group Auto mean in group Manual 
##             17.14737             24.39231

The t-test confirms our assumption (p-value of 0.001374 <= 0.05, therefore we reject H0) and shows that theres statistically significant difference between automatic and manual transmission. The pairs plot also shows that weight is the most strongly correlated with MPG (-0.8677). Lets take this into account during the model selection process.

Modeling

The naive approcah would be to fit a linear model with am as a predictor and mpg as an outcome. Lets try this first.

fit_1 <- lm(mpg ~ am, data = dataset) 
summary(fit_1)$coef
##              Estimate Std. Error   t value     Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept) 17.147368   1.124603 15.247492 1.133983e-15
## amManual     7.244939   1.764422  4.106127 2.850207e-04
summary(fit_1)$r.squared
## [1] 0.3597989

The single variable model explains only 36% of the variance. The Stepvise Algorithm will be used to find the best fitting model automatically.

stepvise_model <- step(lm(mpg ~ . , data = dataset ), trace = 0)

summary(stepvise_model)$coef
##                Estimate Std. Error   t value     Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept) 33.70832390 2.60488618 12.940421 7.733392e-13
## cyl6        -3.03134449 1.40728351 -2.154040 4.068272e-02
## cyl8        -2.16367532 2.28425172 -0.947214 3.522509e-01
## hp          -0.03210943 0.01369257 -2.345025 2.693461e-02
## wt          -2.49682942 0.88558779 -2.819404 9.081408e-03
## amManual     1.80921138 1.39630450  1.295714 2.064597e-01
summary(stepvise_model)$r.squared
## [1] 0.8658799

The algorithm suggests that this model explains 87% of the variance. am, cyl, wt, hp variables are used as predictors for mpg. Lets do a quick check and compare our first model and the one we just discovered.

anova(fit_1, stepvise_model)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: mpg ~ am
## Model 2: mpg ~ cyl + hp + wt + am
##   Res.Df    RSS Df Sum of Sq      F    Pr(>F)    
## 1     30 720.90                                  
## 2     26 151.03  4    569.87 24.527 1.688e-08 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

F statistic is large, p-value is small, so we can confirm that theres a significant difference between the models and the one that the stepwise algorithm suggested is in fact better.

Residuals / diagnostics plots

Residuals plots are available in Appendix C. From the plots of residuals, we can see that there is no pattern in residuals and they are homoscedastic.

head(sort(dfbetas(stepvise_model)[,'amManual'], decreasing = TRUE), n = 2)
##        21        18 
## 0.7305402 0.4292043
head(sort(hatvalues(stepvise_model), decreasing = TRUE), n = 2)
##        31        16 
## 0.4713671 0.2936819

All the outliers do not have significant influence on the model.

Conclusions

From the model output, the manual transmission results in +1.8 mpg compared to the automatic transmission. Every 1000 lbs of the weight of the car result in decrease of mpg by -2.5

Its not clear, however, whether its an effect of the type of transmission itself, or cars in the dataset just tend to be lighter and have less cylinders. More thorough analysis is required.

Appendix A

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(GGally)

## load the data into R
data("mtcars")

## create a data frame tbl
dataset <- tbl_df(mtcars)

## transform to factors
dataset <- mutate(dataset, am = as.factor(am))
dataset <- mutate(dataset, vs = as.factor(vs))
dataset <- mutate(dataset, cyl = as.factor(cyl))
dataset <- mutate(dataset, gear = as.factor(gear))
dataset <- mutate(dataset, carb = as.factor(carb))

## give meaningful labels
levels(dataset$am) <- c("Auto", "Manual")

## https://stackoverflow.com/questions/18617174/r-mtcars-dataset-meaning-of-vs-variable
levels(dataset$vs) <- c("V/Vee", "Straight/inline")

## take a look at the data
head(dataset)
